Diabetic Retinopathy (DR) is a serious eye disease caused by diabetes that can lead to vision loss or blindness if not detected early. 
It occurs when prolonged high blood sugar damages the tiny blood vessels in the retina, the light-sensitive tissue at the back of the eye. 
While regular eye checkups are essential, manual diagnosis is time‑consuming and requires trained specialists. 
Artificial Intelligence offers a powerful solution by automatically analyzing retinal images. Using machine learning and deep learning models,
AI systems can detect early signs of DR quickly and accurately, assisting doctors in diagnosis, reducing workload, and improving patient care. 
Overall, AI plays a crucial role in preventing vision loss by enabling faster, reliable, and affordable screening of diabetic retinopathy.

Existing System:
In the existing system, Diabetic Retinopathy is diagnosed manually by ophthalmologists through eye examinations and analysis of retinal fundus images. 
This process relies heavily on the doctor’s expertise and visual inspection, which can be time‑consuming and costly. 
In rural or resource‑limited areas, access to specialists is scarce, making large‑scale screening difficult and delaying early detection. 
Moreover, human fatigue and errors may reduce diagnostic accuracy, increasing the risk of missed or late identification of the disease.

Disadvantages of existing system:
Detection depends mainly on manual examination by eye specialists
Screening process is slow and time-consuming
Limited availability of ophthalmologists, especially in rural areas
Prone to human error due to fatigue or lack of experience
High cost of regular eye checkups
Difficult to perform large-scale screening
Early stages of the disease may go unnoticed, leading to delayed treatment.

Proposed System:
This introduces Artificial Intelligence (AI) and Machine Learning techniques to automatically detect Diabetic Retinopathy from retinal images. 
By training convolutional neural networks on large datasets, the system can quickly and accurately classify disease severity. 
This reduces the workload of ophthalmologists, saves time, and enables early diagnosis. 
The solution can be deployed in hospitals, clinics, and remote healthcare centers, making eye screening more accessible, affordable, and efficient. 

Advantages of proposed system:
Provides fast and accurate detection of diabetic retinopathy
Enables early diagnosis, preventing vision loss or blindness
Reduces doctors’ workload by assisting in large-scale screening
Saves time and is cost-effective compared to manual examination
Useful in rural and remote areas with limited access to specialists
Produces consistent results and reduces human error
Can be integrated with hospitals, clinics, and telemedicine systems

